The last time I checked, the only difference between Wave's ORS and MKS's ORS is the dll. If you've already installed MKS ORS, you just replace the DLL with the one from Wave's distribution of Interstellar. That's the fix. If you haven't installed MKS ORS yet, quickest is just to install ORS from Wave's distribution of Interstellar and then skip the ORS folder in MKS.

So the game side of things wont change? Pardon my ignorance, I was thinking this would alter the resources used in MKS, I'm glad it wont. :-)

Also, where do I find Wavefunction's distribution of Interstellar? Is it the same as Fractal_UK's on page 1 of this thread?

EDIT:

I'm assuming this is the page: https://github.com/WaveFunctionP/KSPInterstellar/releases

Per a previous post, we should delete the MKS OpenResourceSystem.dll and just use the OpenResourceSystem_1_1_0.dll provided by that link. Just wanted to make sure I understand that correctly.

Edited July 29, 2014 by Kethevin

Bump? Anyone?

I am not seeing anything immediately wrong. Are you using Vistas? Pics of the parent craft would be good. Also pics with the Interstellar MJ manager open on both of the craft would help.

There is only one transceiver on Laythe, well there is 8 total but they are all attached to the same ship. There are no other ships in the Kerbol system that are using microwave energy as of this time. Laythe's atmosphere should be no factor in this for two reasons.

1. The ship worked fine before the update and received all the energy it needed from its parent ship in high orbit.

2. The parent ship (800KM up retro-orbit) is recieaving 5.5GW of power from Kerbin via it's Large Phased Array Transceiver. The opposite side of the ship has another Large Phased Array Transceiver that is emitting at least 5GW down to Laythe.

I need to get some more shots so you know what the whole ship looks like with it's parent ship. I'll send some tonight when I am off work.

https://scontent-b.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xpa1/t1.0-9/10527776_10154419615335052_4976797339952755163_n.jpg

It is not possible to have line of sight to the transmitters on kerbin all of the time with only one ship relaying power in orbit around laythe. You should watch my video on power networks. It explains how everything works.

The thrust issue appears to be a lack of fuel. Have you tried toggling the engine? As you can see, fuel flow is 0.

The power numbers appear to be fine. What you are seeing is automatic reception throttling. The receivers will only receive the amount of power that is being demanded by the vessel, for the most part. This is one of the features of the experimental build.

I am also running the latest in KAS and Procedural Fairings
